Kenya has received about 517,140 Pfizer
COVID-19 vaccines to boost the vaccination drive. The consignment donated by the United States
government via the COVAX facility was received at the Jomo Kenyatta
International Airport (JKIA) on Saturday by Ministry  of Health officials. The U.S embassy in Kenya said the partnership
between the two nations has so far seen 8,173,700 doses of the coronavirus
vaccine arrive in the country. “The United States has donated 8.1 million
doses of Moderna, Pfizer, and Johnson and Johnson vaccines with more on the
way. Proud to be part of a global effort to bring life-saving vaccines to
Kenyans,” said the embassy. The donation marks the 10th from the U.S
since the start of vaccination in 2021 and the second this week alone. On Monday, the U.S donated 1,368,900 doses of
Pfizer to help boost the vaccination campaign in the country. As the country strives to hit the target
27,246,033 of the total population, the ministry has also embarked on
administering booster shots.  Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe on
Saturday reported that a total of 11,987,147 vaccines had been administered
across the country as of January 28, 2022 with 137,031 being booster doses.